'''Riyad Karim Mahrez''' (born 21 February 1991) is a<!-- do not add nationality - it is ambiguous and there is longstanding consensus not to include it --> professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Winger (association football)|right winger]] for [[Al-Ahli Saudi FC|Al-Ahli]]. Born in France, he [[Captain (association football)|captains]] the [[Algeria national football team|Algeria national team]]. He is regarded as one of the best African players of all time.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Brown |first=Jamie |date=7 September 2024 |title=10 Greatest Algeria Players In Football History [Ranked] |url=https://www.givemesport.com/10-greatest-algeria-players-football-history-ranked-mahrez/ |access-date=24 February 2025 |website=GiveMeSport |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=18 December 2023 |title=Algeria : Mahrez, Rabah Madjer, Slimani, here is the ranking of the best players in history |url=https://www.afriquesports.net/en/africa/algeria-mahrez-rabah-madjer-slimani-here-is-the-ranking-of-the-best-players-in-history |access-date=24 February 2025 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |author1=Mark White |date=19 August 2024 |title=Ranked! The 20 best Premier League wingers ever |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/ranked-the-20-best-premier-league-wingers-ever/2 |access-date=30 December 2024 |website=fourfourtwo.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.givemesport.com/greatest-african-players-football-soccer-history/ |title=20 Greatest African Players in Football History Ranked |website=GiveMeSport.com |date=1 October 2024 |first=Hal |last=Fish |access-date=1 October 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |author1=Calum Ritchie |date=11 March 2025 |title=Lineker, Shearer & Richards Rank 10 Best African Stars in Premier League History |url=https://www.givemesport.com/lineker-shearer-richards-best-african-premier-league-history/ |access-date=12 March 2025 |website=GiveMeSport |language=en}}</ref>

Mahrez began his career as a youth player for French club AAS Sarcelles. He turned professional in 2009 with [[Quimper Kerfeunteun F.C.|Quimper]], where he played for only one season before moving to [[Le Havre AC|Le Havre]], spending a total of three years with them, initially playing for their reserve team and then becoming a first-team regular. In January 2014, Mahrez signed for English side [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], helping them win the [[EFL Championship|Championship]] and promotion to the Premier League at the end of his first season. In the 2015–16 season, he was the [[Algerian Footballer of the Year]], the [[PFA Players' Player of the Year]], and was a member of the Premier League [[PFA Team of the Year]] as he helped Leicester City win the [[2015–16 Premier League|Premier League]]. Mahrez signed for Manchester City in 2018, winning the Premier League, [[FA Cup]] and [[EFL Cup]] in his first season. He went on to win a further four league titles, one FA Cup, two EFL Cups and a [[UEFA Champions League]] in [[2022–23 UEFA Champions League|2022–23]] as part of a [[Treble (association football)|continental treble]] whilst at City. On July 2023, he joined the Saudi side Al-Ahli, winning the AFC Champions League Elite and Saudi Super Cup two years later.

Born in France, Mahrez made his international debut for Algeria in 2014, representing the nation at the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] as well as the [[Africa Cup of Nations]] in [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations|2015]], [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations|2017]], [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations|2019]], [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations|2021]], [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations|2023]] and [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations|2025]], winning the 2019 tournament. In 2016, he was named [[Confederation of African Football|CAF]]'s [[African Footballer of the Year]].

==Early life==
Mahrez was born in [[Clichy, Hauts-de-Seine|Clichy]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sofoot.com/breves/le-psg-et-lom-sarrachent-un-joueur
|title=Le PSG et l’OM s’arrachent un joueur|date=25 May 2010|access-date=11 April 2026|language=fr|publisher=So Foot}}</ref> to an Algerian father and a mother of Algerian and Moroccan descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.djazairess.com/fr/letemps/140838|title=Riyad Mahrez : "On a une équipe capable de faire de belles choses"|date=10 January 2015|access-date=6 March 2016|language=fr|publisher=DjaZairess}}</ref> His father Ahmed was from [[Beni Snous]], [[Tlemcen Province]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lebuteur.com/article/detail?id=33412|title=Mahrez honoré à Tlemcen|date=4 June 2015|access-date=28 January 2016|language=fr|publisher=El Heddaf}}</ref> Growing up, Mahrez would regularly spend his holidays in Algeria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lebuteur.com/article/detail?id=4572&titre=comment-la-faf-a-chipe-mahrez-au-maroc|title=Comment la FAF a chipé Mahrez au Maroc|date=9 May 2014|access-date=10 June 2014|language=fr|publisher=Le Buteur}}</ref><ref name=doyle>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/sep/12/leicester-city-riyad-mahrez-father-dream-algeria-world-cup|title=Leicester City's Riyad Mahrez is fast fulfilling his late father's dreams|date=12 September 2015|access-date=14 September 2015|author=Paul Doyle|work=The Guardian}}</ref> His childhood friends included fellow footballers, such as [[Wissam Ben Yedder]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ben Yedder's unquestionable self-belief driving him to reach new heights|url=https://www.uefa.com/news-media/news/023f-0f8e5936fefa-b8ce1083deae-1000--ben-yedder-s-unquestionable-self-belief-driving-him-to-re/|access-date=23 November 2017|publisher=UEFA|date=12 December 2017}}</ref>

Mahrez's father had played football in Algeria.<ref name=doyle/> When Mahrez was fifteen, his father died of a heart attack. He reflected that "I don't know if I started to be more serious but after the death of my dad things started to go for me. Maybe in my head, I wanted it more".<ref name=doyle/>

==Club career==

===Early career===
Although often overlooked by teams due to his slender build, Mahrez developed ball skills that brought him attention.<ref name=doyle/>

He joined AAS Sarcelles in 2004.<ref name="journey">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35688719|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester forward's journey to top of Premier League|date=10 March 2016|access-date=10 March 2016|author=Steve Crossman|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He had a two-month trial at Scottish club [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]], but left due to the cold weather.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11712/10262801/leicesters-riyad-mahrez-once-fled-a-trial-at-st-mirren-because-of-the-cold|title=Riyad Mahrez once fled a trial at St Mirren on a borrowed bike|last=Valente|first=Allan|date=30 April 2016|website=Sky Sports}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57151780 |title=Riyad Mahrez: Paul Potts, JLS & a getaway bike - the story behind Man City winger's St Mirren trial |first=Nick |last=McPheat |website=BBC Sport |date=26 May 2021 |accessdate=26 May 2021}}</ref>

In 2009, Mahrez joined [[Championnat National 2|CFA]] side [[Quimper Kerfeunteun F.C.|Quimper]] from AAS Sarcelles, making 22 appearances and scoring 2 goals in his first season with the club.<ref name="Quimper">{{cite web|url=http://stat2foot.com/qrclubs/quimper0910.htm |language=fr |title=QUIMPER 17e CFA Groupe D |publisher=Stat2foot.com |access-date=11 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140111075652/http://stat2foot.com/qrclubs/quimper0910.htm |archive-date=11 January 2014 }}</ref> While playing for Quimper, he lived with [[Mathias Pogba]].<ref name="journey"/>

He joined [[Le Havre AC|Le Havre]] in 2010, turning down offers from leading French teams [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]] and [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]] to join them, being enticed by Le Havre's youth system.<ref name=doyle/> He initially played for their reserve team, Le Havre II, before going on to play 60 times and score 6 goals for the first team in the French [[Ligue 2]] from 2011 until leaving in January 2014.<ref name="SW"/><ref>{{LFP|id=mahrez-riyad|name=Riyad Mahrez}}</ref> He criticised Ligue 2 for what he saw as reliance on defence and teams aiming for a goalless draw in every match.<ref name=doyle/>

===Leicester City===
[[File:Riyad Mahrez.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Mahrez playing for Leicester City in 2014]]
[[File:Mahrez free kick 1 (16476351346).jpg|thumb|upright|303px|Mahrez taking a free kick away against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in February 2015.]]

====2013–14 season====
While Mahrez was playing for Le Havre, English [[EFL Championship|Championship]] club [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]'s scout [[Steve Walsh (scout)|Steve Walsh]] was monitoring teammate [[Ryan Mendes]], but was instead impressed by Mahrez.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leicester City star Riyad Mahrez not target of original scouting mission says head of recruitment|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Riyad-target-scouting-mission/story-28029571-detail/story.html|access-date=26 April 2016|work=Leicester Mercury|date=22 October 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151129020313/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Riyad-target-scouting-mission/story-28029571-detail/story.html|archive-date=29 November 2015}}</ref> Mahrez had never heard of Leicester, whom he initially presumed to be a rugby club.<ref name="street">{{cite news|last1=Brewin|first1=Joe|title=Riyad Mahrez: The street-schooled dreamer whose ambition knew no limits|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/riyad-mahrez-street-schooled-dreamer-whose-ambition-knew-no-limits|access-date=5 May 2021|work=FourFourTwo|date=25 April 2016}}</ref> On 11 January 2014, he was signed by Leicester City on a three-and-a-half-year contract for around £450,000.<ref name="street"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lcfc.com/news/article/110114-riyad-mahrez-signs-for-leicester-city-1287938.aspx|title=Riyad Mahrez Signs For Leicester City|date=11 January 2014|access-date=11 January 2014|publisher=Leicester City F.C.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/25639726|title=Transfer window: Riyad Mahrez joins Leicester from Le Havre|date=11 January 2014|access-date=13 January 2014|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> His friends and family were initially sceptical of a move to English football due to its physical nature, believing that his style of play would be more suited to Spain.<ref name=doyle/>

Mahrez made his debut on 25 January 2014, coming on in the 79th minute as a substitute replacing fellow winger [[Lloyd Dyer]], in the 2–0 win against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/25789370|title=Leicester 2&nbsp;– 0 Middlesbrough|date=25 January 2014|access-date=25 January 2014|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> After making four substitute appearances for Leicester, including scoring his first goal for the club, an 82nd-minute equaliser against [[Leicester City F.C.–Nottingham Forest F.C. rivalry|local rivals]] [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]], manager Nigel Pearson announced in February 2014 that he thought Mahrez was ready to start games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/26278839|title=Riyad Mahrez: Nigel Pearson says winger ready to start games|date=21 February 2014|access-date=23 February 2014|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Leicester ended [[2013–14 Football League Championship|the season]] as winners of the Championship, returning to the Premier League for the first time in ten years.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leicester City promoted to Premier League after 10-year absence|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/26906091|access-date=20 December 2015|website=BBC Sport|date=5 April 2014}}</ref>

====2014–15 season====
Mahrez made his Premier League debut on 16 August 2014, and scored his first goal in the division on 4 October 2014 in a 2–2 draw with [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].<ref name="SB"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-City-news-Unknown-Riyad-Mahrez-making/story-23059629-detail/story.html|title='Unknown' Riyad Mahrez making impressive strides, says Nigel Pearson|date=8 October 2014|access-date=16 October 2014|publisher=Leicester Mercury|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020150217/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-City-news-Unknown-Riyad-Mahrez-making/story-23059629-detail/story.html|archive-date=20 October 2014}}</ref> Mahrez was part of the Leicester team that won seven of its final nine matches of the season to avoid relegation to the Football League. He scored both goals in a 2–0 defeat of [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] on 9 May<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32561831|title=Leicester City 2–0 Southampton|work=BBC Sport }}</ref> and ended [[2014–15 Leicester City F.C. season|the season]] with four goals and three assists from 30 appearances.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://m.premierleague.com/en-gb/players/playerprofile.html/riyad-mahrez|title=Riyad Mahrez|access-date=20 December 2015|work=Premier League|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222111631/http://m.premierleague.com/en-gb/players/playerprofile.html/riyad-mahrez|archive-date=22 December 2015}}</ref>

====2015–16 season====
He signed a new four-year contract with Leicester in August 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/33789418|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester City winger signs new contract|date=5 August 2015|access-date=6 August 2015|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 8 August 2015, Mahrez scored two goals in the season opener against [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in a 4–2 home win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2015/08/08/england/premier-league/leicester-city-fc/sunderland-association-football-club/2043050/|title=Leicester City 4–2 Sunderland|date=8 August 2015|access-date=10 August 2015|publisher=Soccerway}}</ref> He was later described as the club's "match winner" by captain [[Wes Morgan]], following "superb form" which saw him score four goals in the first three games of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/t-rely-Mahrez-time-ndash-Wes/story-27760222-detail/story.html|title=We can't rely on Riyad Mahrez all the time, says Wes Morgan|date=9 September 2015|access-date=9 September 2015|publisher=Leicester Mercury|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911235806/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/t-rely-Mahrez-time-ndash-Wes/story-27760222-detail/story.html|archive-date=11 September 2015}}</ref>

After scoring four goals in the opening four games of the 2015–16 season, Mahrez was nominated for the [[Premier League Player of the Month]] award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34216391|title=Andre Ayew & Manuel Pellegrini win Premier League awards|date=11 September 2015|access-date=13 September 2015|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> By 3 November 2015, he had scored seven goals in 10 Premier League games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34709767|title=Riyad Mahrez wary of Leicester City's rising expectations|date=3 November 2015|access-date=3 November 2015|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 5 December, Mahrez scored a hat-trick as Leicester defeated [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] 3–0 to go top of the Premier League, putting him on ten league goals for the season and making him the first Algerian to score a [[List of Premier League hat-tricks|Premier League hat-trick]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pritchard|first1=Dafydd|title=Swansea 0–3 Leicester|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34951743|access-date=20 December 2015|website=BBC Sport|date=5 December 2015}}</ref> Mahrez and his midfield partners [[Marc Albrighton]], [[N'Golo Kanté]] and [[Danny Drinkwater]] received plaudits for their part in Leicester's early season run of form,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Laurence|first1=Martin|title=Why Riyad Mahrez, and not Jamie Vardy, has been the player of the season so far|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/who-scored-blog/2015/dec/08/riyad-mahrez-jamie-vardy-player-season-premier-league|access-date=17 January 2016|work=The Guardian|date=8 December 2015}}</ref> and manager [[Claudio Ranieri]] described Mahrez and forward [[Jamie Vardy]] as "priceless" ahead of the January transfer window.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jamie Vardy and Riyad Mahrez priceless – Claudio Ranieri|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35098801|access-date=17 January 2016|website=BBC Sport|date=15 December 2015}}</ref>

In January 2016 Mahrez's transfer value was said to have risen from £4.5 million to £30.1 million, ranking him among the top 50 most valuable players in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|title = Leicester City winger Riyad Mahrez ranked in top 50 most valuable players in Europe at nearly £30m|url = http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-City-winger-Riyad-Mahrez-ranked-50/story-28475654-detail/story.html|publisher = Leicester Mercury|date = 6 January 2016|access-date = 7 February 2016|archive-date = 2 June 2022|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20220602220617/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Leicester-City-winger-Riyad-Mahrez-ranked-50/story-28475654-detail/story.html|url-status = dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Leicester City: Why we are all rooting for the Foxes|url = https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/35480812|publisher = BBC Sport|date = 3 February 2016|access-date = 7 February 2016}}</ref> In the same year, Mahrez's popularity in his homeland led Leicester to have over almost three times as many [[Facebook]] fans in Algeria than in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|title=African players in the Premier League|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35844104|access-date=18 March 2016|website=BBC Sport|date=18 March 2016}}</ref> The barbershop in Sarcelles that he frequented from his childhood became a destination for fans from as far as Belgium, desiring the same haircut.<ref name="journey"/>

Mahrez was one of four Leicester players named in the [[PFA Team of the Year]] in April 2016,<ref name="PFATeam">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36106596|title=PFA awards: Leicester and Spurs dominate Premier League team|date=21 April 2016|access-date=21 April 2016|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> and later that month he won the [[PFA Players' Player of the Year]] award.<ref name="PFAPlayer">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36124713|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester City forward named PFA Player of the Year|date=25 April 2016|access-date=25 April 2016|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He was the first African to earn the accolade.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bargain of the century Riyad Mahrez first African to win EPL player of the season|url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/sport/football/bargain-century-riyad-mahrez-first-african-win-epl-player-season|access-date=25 April 2016|agency=Associated Press|publisher=TVNZ|date=25 April 2016}}</ref> When Leicester finished the season as champions, Mahrez became the first Algerian to win a Premier League medal.<ref name="PL">{{cite news|title=Leicester City: The ridiculous statistics|url=http://www.football365.com/news/leicester-city-the-ridiculous-statistics|access-date=3 May 2016|publisher=Football 365|date=3 May 2016}}</ref>

====2016–17 season====
{{Quote box |width=35% |align=right |quoted=1 |quote=I am fiercely ambitious and feel now is the time to move on to a new experience. I've always enjoyed a good relationship with the chairman and everyone at the club, and I hope I have been able to repay the faith shown to me by my performances and commitment on the pitch during my time here. |salign=right |source=— Mahrez speaking to ''[[The Guardian]]'' about his desire to leave Leicester City.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/may/30/riyad-mahrez-leicester-city-transfer-request-time-to-move-on |title=Riyad Mahrez asks to leave Leicester: 'I feel now is the time to move on' |last=Aarons |first=Ed |date=30 May 2017 |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=3 June 2017}}</ref>}}

He signed a new four-year contract with Leicester in August 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37112706|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester City winger signs new four-year deal|date=17 August 2016|access-date=18 August 2016|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He was nominated for the [[2016 Ballon d'Or|Ballon d'Or]] in October 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37748717|title=Ballon d'Or: Jamie Vardy, Riyad Mahrez, Gareth Bale & Sergio Aguero on shortlist|date=24 October 2016|access-date=29 October 2016|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> finishing seventh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dzfoot.com/2016/12/12/ballon-dor-2016-ryad-mahrez-7e-95861.php|title=Ballon d'Or 2016 : Ryad Mahrez 7e !|date=12 December 2016|access-date=12 December 2016|language=fr|publisher=dzfoot.com}}</ref> He won the [[BBC African Footballer of the Year]] award in December 2016.<ref name="BBCAfrican">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38210161|title=Riyad Mahrez wins BBC African Footballer of the Year 2016 award|date=12 December 2016|access-date=12 December 2016|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Mahrez did not offer a big season especially with the decline in the level of Leicester, but helped the team's arrival in the [[2016–17 UEFA Champions League#Quarter-finals|quarter-finals of the Champions League]] for the first time, scoring four goals and two assists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39275115|title=Leicester reach Champions League quarter-finals and threaten to defy logic again|date=15 March 2017|access-date=3 June 2017|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 6 May, Mahrez played his 100th Premier League game for Leicester, against [[Watford F.C.|Watford]], scoring in the process.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fr.starafrica.com/football/articles/premier-league-36e-j-100e-match-et-6e-de-mahrez/|title=Premier League (36e J) : 100e match et 6e but de Mahrez !|date=8 May 2017|access-date=3 June 2017|publisher=fr.starafrica.com|archive-date=7 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180807034230/https://fr.starafrica.com/football/articles/premier-league-36e-j-100e-match-et-6e-de-mahrez/|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dzfoot.com/2017/05/06/angleterre-6e-but-de-mahrez-pour-sa-100e-en-pl-102774.php|title=Angleterre : 6e but de Mahrez pour sa 100e en PL|date=6 May 2017|access-date=3 June 2017|publisher=dzfoot.com}}</ref>

====2017–18 season====
At the end of the 2016–17 season, Mahrez announced that he wished to leave the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40098443|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester forward releases statement asking to leave the club|date=30 May 2017|access-date=30 May 2017|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Following the announcement, [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] manager [[Arsène Wenger]] stated his interest in signing Mahrez,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40142219|title=Riyad Mahrez: Arsenal boss Arsene Wenger interested in Leicester winger|date=3 June 2017|access-date=4 June 2017|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> and Italian side [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] had a bid for Mahrez rejected in July 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40679721|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester reject Roma bid for Algeria winger|date=21 July 2017|access-date=21 July 2017|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> In August 2017 he spoke of his "focus" despite his uncertain future at the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40911451|title=Riyad Mahrez: Algeria winger 'focused' despite uncertain future|date=12 August 2017|access-date=22 August 2017|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> The [[Algerian Football Federation]] reported on 31 August, the last day of the transfer window, that it had allowed him to leave the national team and travel quickly to Europe in order to complete his transfer to an interested club; this transfer did not materialise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faf.dz/mahrez-autorise-a-aller-officialiser-son-transfert-vers-son-nouveau-club/|title=Mahrez autorisé à aller officialiser son transfert vers son nouveau club|date=31 August 2017|access-date=31 August 2017|publisher=Algerian Football Federation|language=fr|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831042018/http://www.faf.dz/mahrez-autorise-a-aller-officialiser-son-transfert-vers-son-nouveau-club/|archive-date=31 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Riyad Mahrez remains at Leicester despite being released from Algeria squad|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41105659|date=1 September 2017|access-date=6 October 2017|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> In January 2018 he again asked for a transfer away from the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42875848|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester City winger hands in transfer request as Man City make bid|date=30 January 2018|access-date=31 January 2018|author=Simon Stone|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> After a move to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] fell through,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42895613|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester will 'help' winger after Man City walk away from potential deal|date=1 February 2018|access-date=6 February 2018|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Mahrez stopped attending training at Leicester.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42918406|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester forward misses training for fourth day|date=2 February 2018|access-date=2 February 2018|author=Simon Stone|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> His behaviour was criticised by commentator and former player [[Chris Sutton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42953586|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester midfielder acting like 'big baby' since move fell through – Chris Sutton|date=6 February 2018|access-date=6 February 2018|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Mahrez was critical about the "untrue assumptions" about his absence from the team,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43001730|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester winger criticises 'untrue assumptions' about absence|date=9 February 2018|access-date=12 February 2018|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> and later thanked his teammates for their support.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43331305|title=Riyad Mahrez: Leicester winger says team-mates stood by him|date=8 March 2018|access-date=9 March 2018|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

===Manchester City===
====2018–19 season====
On 10 July 2018, [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] confirmed the signing of Mahrez on a five-year contract. The transfer fee of £60m made Mahrez the [[List of most expensive association football transfers|most expensive African footballer]], and also Manchester City's most expensive signing and a record transfer fee received by [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{cite news|title=City sign Riyad Mahrez from Leicester|url=https://www.mancity.com/news/first-team/first-team-news/2018/july/man-city-sign-riyad-mahrez-leicester|access-date=10 July 2018|date=10 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44709129?ns_mchannel=social&ns_campaign=bbc_sport&ns_source=facebook&ns_linkname=sport |title=Riyad Mahrez: Manchester City sign winger from Leicester for £60m |website=BBC Sport |date=10 July 2018 |access-date=10 July 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=City sign Riyad Mahrez from Leicester|url=https://www.mancity.com/news/first-team/first-team-news/2018/july/man-city-sign-riyad-mahrez-leicester|publisher=Manchester City F.C.|date=10 July 2018}}</ref> He stated he wanted to win the Champions League with the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44809552|title=Riyad Mahrez: I want to win Champions League with Manchester City|date=12 July 2018|website=BBC Sport|access-date=16 July 2018}}</ref> He made his debut as a starter on 5 August, as City defeated Chelsea 2–0 to win the [[2018 FA Community Shield]] at [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref name=shield>{{cite news |last1=Bevan |first1=Chris |title=Chelsea 0–2 Manchester City |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44995783 |access-date=5 August 2018 |website=BBC Sport |date=5 August 2018}}</ref> On 22 September 2018, coming on as a substitute in the 61st minute Mahrez scored a brace for the Citizens against [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], The first goal was his first with Manchester City.<ref>{{cite news |title=Riyad Mahrez double caps five-star Manchester City's rout of Cardiff |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/sep/22/cardiff-manchester-city-premier-league-match-report |access-date=16 November 2018 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=22 September 2018}}</ref>

On 29 October 2018, Mahrez scored the only goal for Manchester City in a 1–0 away victory against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]. He dedicated the goal to [[Vichai Srivaddhanaprabha]], the former owner of his previous club Leicester City, who had recently [[2018 Leicester City F.C. helicopter crash|died in a helicopter crash]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46026701|title=Leicester helicopter crash: Riyad Mahrez dedicates Man City goal to Foxes owner|website=BBC Sport|date=29 October 2018|access-date=6 November 2018}}</ref> On 24 February 2019, Mahrez won his second title with Manchester City by winning the [[2018–19 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], also won the best player of the EFL Cup although he did not participate in the final.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bhardwaj |first1=Vaishali |title=Man City beat Chelsea to win EFL Cup Final after Wembley penalty shootout |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/chelsea-vs-man-city-efl-cup-final-report-result-wembley-a4075136.html |work=[[Evening Standard]] |date=24 February 2019 |access-date=15 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=League Cup: City s'impose aux tirs au but sans Mahrez |url=http://www.dzfoot.com/2019/02/24/league-cup-city-simpose-aux-tirs-au-but-sans-mahrez-145865.php |work=dzfoot.com |date=24 February 2019 |access-date=15 March 2019}}</ref>

At the end of his first season with Manchester City, despite having "limited playing time" (including just 14 league starts),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48260081|title=Manchester City: Riyad Mahrez happy at Premier League champions|date=13 May 2019|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Mahrez won the Premier League title for the second time, and his first with Manchester City, becoming the second African player to win the title with two different clubs after [[Kolo Touré]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester City win back-to-back Premier League titles after surviving early Brighton scare |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/05/12/brighton-vs-manchester-city-premier-league-live-score-updates/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512130633/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/05/12/brighton-vs-manchester-city-premier-league-live-score-updates/ |archive-date=12 May 2019 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |access-date=14 May 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=12 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=PL : Mahrez passeur et buteur, Man. City Champion ! |url=http://www.dzfoot.com/2019/05/12/pl-mahrez-passeur-et-buteur-city-champion-151231.php |access-date=14 May 2019 |publisher=dzfoot.com |date=12 May 2019}}</ref> Mahrez said he would not leave City despite his lack of game time, claiming that he knew his first season would be difficult and he had come to a stable team with good players but he trusted his potential.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mercato : Mahrez, " Je n'irai nul part ! " |url=http://www.dzfoot.com/2019/05/14/mahrez-je-nirai-nul-part-151364.php |access-date=14 May 2019 |publisher=dzfoot.com |date=14 May 2019}}</ref> A week after in the [[2019 FA Cup Final|FA Cup final]], he achieved his fourth title of the season after beating [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] 6–0 becoming the first African player to complete an English domestic [[Treble (association football)|treble]], as he earlier won the [[2018–19 EFL Cup]] and the [[2018–19 Premier League]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester City smash six past Watford in FA Cup final to win historic domestic treble |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/05/18/fa-cup-final-manchester-city-vs-watford-live-score-latest-updates/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220111/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/05/18/fa-cup-final-manchester-city-vs-watford-live-score-latest-updates/ |archive-date=11 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=18 May 2019}}{{cbignore}}</ref>

====2019–20 season====
In August 2019, Mahrez missed the [[2019 FA Community Shield]] over concerns about medicine he had been given by the Algerian national team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49230288|title=Riyad Mahrez: Medicine concern kept Algerian out of Man City team|date=4 August 2019|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> The Algerian FA described it as a "non-event".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49263769|title=Riyad Mahrez: Concerns over medicine taken by Man City winger a 'non-event', says Algerian FA|date=7 August 2019|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> Mahrez later started in Manchester City's 5–0 opening day away win against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], being involved in all 5 of his side's goals, providing two assists for hat-trick scorer [[Raheem Sterling]] and winning a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] for [[Sergio Agüero]] to eventually score after a retake.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49215984|title=West Ham 0–5 Manchester City|date=10 August 2019|access-date=17 August 2019|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

====2020–21 season====
On 28 November 2020, Mahrez scored his first hat-trick for City in a 5–0 home league win over [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Stone|first=Simon|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/55025784 |title=Manchester City 5-0 Burnley: Riyad Mahrez hat-trick in dominant win |website=[[BBC Sport]] |date=28 November 2020 |access-date=28 November 2020}}</ref> On 4 May 2021, Mahrez scored both goals in a 2–0 home win over Paris Saint-Germain in the second leg of the Champions League [[2020–21 UEFA Champions League knockout phase#Manchester City v Paris Saint-Germain|semi-finals]], and by scoring via a [[Free kick (association football)|direct free kick]] in a 2–1 away win a week earlier,<ref>{{cite news |last=McNulty|first=Phil|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/56880443 |title=Paris St-Germain 1-2 Man City: Kevin de Bruyne & Riyad Mahrez give City advantage in Champions League|website=[[BBC Sport]] |date=28 April 2021 |access-date=29 April 2021}}</ref> he led City through to the first European Cup [[2021 UEFA Champions League Final|final]] in the club's history.<ref>{{cite news |last=McNulty|first=Phil|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/56973031 |title=Man City 2-0 Paris St-Germain (4-1 on aggregate): City into Champions League final |website=[[BBC Sport]] |date=4 May 2021 |access-date=4 May 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/man-city-psg-result-champions-league-b1842146.html|title=Riyad Mahrez strikes twice to book sublime Man City's place in Champions League final|date=4 May 2021|website=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/2021/may/04/hail-riyad-mahrez-manchester-citys-oddly-underrated-ball-playing-genius|title=Elegant, merciless and getting better: Mahrez is an underrated genius &#124; Barney Ronay|date=4 May 2021|website=The Guardian}}</ref> However, his team lost 1–0 to Chelsea in the final, with his half-volley from the edge of the penalty area sailing just over the crossbar in the final minute of stoppage time.<ref>{{cite web |last=Sanders |first=Emma |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/live/football/54074842?page=3 |title='Tuchel is a magician' - reaction as Chelsea win Champions League final |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 May 2021 }}</ref>

====2021–22 season====
On 6 March 2022, he scored a brace in a 4–1 win over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/60531492 |title=Manchester City 4–1 Manchester United |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 March 2022 }}</ref> In the [[2021–22 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], he scored a record of seven goals, with the last being in the semi-final second leg away match against [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] to grant his team a 1–0 lead before being subbed off.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/mahrez-fans-slam-guardiola-s-decision-to-substitute-manchester-city-star-against-real-madrid-it-was-so-needless/blt6506963f36ec7a29 |title=Mahrez: Fans slam Guardiola's decision to substitute Manchester City star against Real Madrid - 'It was so needless' |publisher=Goal.com |date=5 May 2022 }}</ref> However, the opponent managed to turn the tie by late goals and extra-time to win 3–1 (6–5 on aggregate) and reach the final.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2022/may/04/real-madrid-v-manchester-city-champions-league-semi-final-second-leg-live |title=Real Madrid 3–1 Man City |work=The Guardian |date=4 May 2022 }}</ref>

Mahrez scored 24 goals in all competitions, his personal best record in one season, to be shortlisted for the [[2022 Ballon d'Or|Ballon d'Or]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/seven-city-players-nominated-ballon-d-or-yashin-trophy-63795902 |title=Six Manchester City players have been nominated for the 2021/22 Ballon d'Or award, while Ederson is shortlisted for the Yashin Trophy |publisher=Manchester City |date=12 August 2022 |access-date=23 April 2023 |archive-date=13 August 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220813013550/https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/seven-city-players-nominated-ballon-d-or-yashin-trophy-63795902 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

==== 2022–23 season ====
On 15 July 2022, Manchester City announced Mahrez had signed a two-year contract extension that would keep him at the club until 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |date=15 July 2022 |title=Mahrez signs new two-year deal at Man City |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/soccer-transfers/story/4701457/man-citys-riyad-mahrez-signs-new-two-year-contract-extension |access-date=15 July 2022 |website=ESPN.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/62184136|title=Man City winger Mahrez signs new contract|work=BBC Sport }}</ref> On 22 February 2023, he scored his 20th goal in the Champions League in a 1–1 away draw against [[RB Leipzig]] in the round of 16, to become the fifth African player to achieve this feat.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/news/riyad-mahrez-scores-historic-champions-league-goal-but-manchester-city-can-only-draw-with-rb-leipzig |title=Riyad Mahrez scores historic Champions League goal – but Manchester City can only draw with RB Leipzig |publisher=FourFourTwo |date=22 February 2023 }}</ref> On 22 April 2023, he became the first player since [[Alex Dawson]] in 1958<ref>{{cite news |last=Mumford |first=Jack |title=Mahrez becomes first City player to score hat-trick at Wembley |date=22 April 2023 |url=https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/riyad-mahrez-fa-cup-semi-final-hat-trick-63817781 |access-date=23 April 2023 |website=Manchester City FC |language=en }}</ref> to score a [[hat-trick#Association football|hat-trick]] in a [[2022–23 FA Cup|FA Cup]] [[FA Cup semi-finals|semi-final]], notching three times against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] in a 3–0 win.<ref>{{Cite news |date=22 April 2023 |title=FA Cup semi-final: Mahrez scores hat-trick sends Man City into final |language=en-GB |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/live/football/65032284 |access-date=22 April 2023}}</ref> On 10 June, Manchester City won 1–0 against [[Inter Milan]] in the [[2023 UEFA Champions League final|Champions League final]], in which he became the second Algerian to win the competition after [[Rabah Madjer]] in 1987.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newarab.com/news/mahrez-becomes-1st-algerian-win-cl-title-over-30-years |title=Riyad Mahrez becomes first Algerian to win UEFA Champions League in over 30 years |publisher=The New Arab |date=11 June 2023 }}</ref> In addition, he managed to win the continental treble with his club, despite not featuring in both [[2023 FA Cup final|FA Cup]] and Champions League finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mancity.com/citytv/city-plus/riyad-mahrez-story-manchester-city-63812569 |title=The Riyad Mahrez Story |publisher=Manchester City FC |date=10 July 2023 }}</ref>

===Al-Ahli===
On 19 July 2023, BBC reported that Manchester City had agreed a deal for Mahrez to join [[Saudi Professional League|Saudi Pro League]] club [[Al Ahli Saudi FC|Al Ahli]] for a transfer fee of £30 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66250638 |title=Riyad Mahrez: Manchester City agree £30m deal for Al-Ahli to sign Algeria winger |publisher=BBC Sport |date=19 July 2023 }}</ref> The transfer was confirmed on 28 July 2023, with Mahrez signing a contract to 2027.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mahrez joins Al-Ahli |url=https://www.mancity.com/news/mens/riyad-mahrez-joins-al-ahli-manchester-city-63826097 |access-date=28 July 2023 |publisher=Manchester City |date=28 July 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66339153|title=Mahrez makes £30m move from Man City to Al-Ahli|work=BBC Sport }}</ref> On 11 August 2023, Mahrez provided his first assist for Al-Ahli in his first competitive game for the side, assisting [[Roberto Firmino]] in a victory against [[Al-Hazem F.C.|Al-Hazem]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66479625|title=Al-Ahli 3-1 Al-Hazem|work=BBC Sport }}</ref> A week later, on 17 August, he scored his first goal for the club in a 3–1 away win over [[Al-Khaleej FC|Al-Khaleej]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/682086/al-ahli-al-khaleej |title=Al Khaleej 1–3 Al Ahli |publisher=ESPN |date=17 August 2023 }}</ref>

In the 2024–25 season, he won the [[2024–25 AFC Champions League Elite|AFC Champions League Elite]] with Al Ahli.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.beinsports.com/en-us/soccer/afc-champions-league/articles/mahrez-ranks-afc-champions-league-title-alongside-premier-league-ucl-honours-2025-05-04 |title=Mahrez ranks AFC Champions League title alongside Premier League, UCL honours |publisher=beIN SPORTS |date=4 May 2025 }}</ref> Hence, he became, along with teammates Roberto Firmino and [[Édouard Mendy]], one of the first players to have won both European and Asian club titles.<ref>{{cite web |last=McVitie |first=Peter |url=https://www.goal.com/en/lists/roberto-firmino-edouard-mendy-riyad-mahrez-history-win-asian-european-champions-leagues-liverpool-al-ahli-final-kawasaki-frontale/blt9445eb2f66be2a00#cs2ce14c5cfb43d6ee |title=Roberto Firmino, Edouard Mendy and Riyad Mahrez make history as first stars to win Asian and European Champions Leagues after ex-Liverpool forward inspires Al-Ahli to final win against Kawasaki Frontale |publisher=Goal.com |date=3 May 2025 }}</ref> The following season, he played a role in the team's continental campaign during the [[2025–26 AFC Champions League Elite|2025–26 season]], which culminated in a 1–0 extra-time victory over [[FC Machida Zelvia|Machida Zelvia]] in the [[2026 AFC Champions League Elite final|final]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/fifa-club-world-cup/articles/ah-ahli-win-afc-champions-league
 |title=Al Ahli claim back-to-back AFC Champions League titles |publisher=The AFC |date=25 April 2026 }}</ref>

==International career==
[[File:Riyad Mahrez - 2014 World Cup.jpg|thumbnail|right|upright|Mahrez playing for [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] at the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]]]]

In November 2013, the French-born Mahrez expressed his desire to represent [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] internationally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dzfoot.com/news-14868-verts-riyad-mahrez-je-sais-que-je-peux-jouer-en-en.php |title=Riyad Mahrez "Je sais que je peux jouer en EN" |trans-title=Riyad Mahrez "I know that I can play in the national team" |language=fr |date=8 November 2013 |access-date=11 January 2014 |publisher=DZFoot |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110003551/http://www.dzfoot.com/news-14868-verts-riyad-mahrez-je-sais-que-je-peux-jouer-en-en.php |archive-date=10 November 2013}}</ref> He was called up to the provisional Algeria squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/27374742|title=World Cup 2014: Nabil Bentaleb in Algeria's 30-man squad|date=12 May 2014|access-date=12 May 2014|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 31 May 2014, Mahrez made his international debut for the ''Desert Foxes'' as a starter in a pre-World Cup friendly match against [[Armenia national football team|Armenia]], and he was subsequently called up to the full squad for the tournament on 2 June.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lcfc.com/news/article/020614-world-cup-beckons-for-mahrez-1592375.aspx|title=World Cup Beckons For Mahrez|date=2 June 2014|access-date=2 June 2014|publisher=Leicester City F.C.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140605054435/http://www.lcfc.com/news/article/020614-world-cup-beckons-for-mahrez-1592375.aspx|archive-date=5 June 2014}}</ref> The Algerian media were critical of his inclusion and alleged that he had paid manager [[Vahid Halilhodžić]] for a place in the squad.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tironi|first1=Hrvoje|title=People accused Mahrez of giving me money to go to the World Cup! – Halilhodzic|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2565/exclusive/2016/02/13/20291192/people-accused-mahrez-of-giving-me-money-to-go-to-the-world|access-date=4 May 2016|publisher=Goal.com|date=13 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=msn>{{cite news|last1=Ouali|first1=Amer|title=Leicester City and Riyad Mahrez gaining fans in Algeria|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/sports/premier-league/leicester-city-and-riyad-mahrez-gaining-fans-in-algeria/ar-BBq9qOz|access-date=4 May 2016|agency=AFP|publisher=MSN|date=29 February 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603102929/http://www.msn.com/en-us/sports/premier-league/leicester-city-and-riyad-mahrez-gaining-fans-in-algeria/ar-BBq9qOz|archive-date=3 June 2016}}</ref> Mahrez played in the opening group game against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]], then was dropped for the remainder of the tournament, in which Algeria reached the last 16.<ref name=msn/>

On 15 October 2014, Mahrez scored his first international goal, as well as setting up [[Islam Slimani]] in Algeria's 3–0, [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations qualification|Africa Cup of Nations]] qualifier against [[Malawi national football team|Malawi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lcfc.com/news/article/151014-mahrez-stars-in-algeria-win-2017946.aspx|title=Mahrez Stars In Algeria Win|date=15 October 2014|access-date=16 October 2014|publisher=Leicester City F.C.}}</ref> In December 2014 he was announced as a member of Algeria's squad for the [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations|final tournament in Equatorial Guinea]] for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30477709|title=Nations Cup 2015: Newcastle's Mehdi Abeid in Algeria squad|date=15 December 2014|access-date=18 December 2014|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> His first meeting was against [[South Africa national football team|South Africa]] where he participated in the 60 minutes before the change in the second throw against [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] substitute in the last 20 minutes where the Algerian team were defeated by a single goal. In their last game in the [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations Group C|group stage]] against [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]], Mahrez led the national team to the quarter-finals, scoring the first goal of a match ending 2–0.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hughes|first1=Ian|title=Senegal 0–2 Algeria|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/30891881|access-date=20 December 2015|website=BBC Sport|date=27 January 2015}}</ref> Then against [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]] gave assists for [[El Arabi Hillel Soudani]] were not enough to exclude from the quarter-finals 3–1.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hughes|first1=Ian|title=Ivory Coast 3–1 Algeria|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/30971819|access-date=1 February 2015|website=BBC Sport|date=16 January 2017}}</ref> then in the second Round of the [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification – CAF second round|2018 World Cup qualifier]] against [[Tanzania national football team|Tanzania]] helped Mahrez in the team qualified for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification – CAF third round|group stage]] where he scored a goal and assists for [[Carl Medjani]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hughes|first1=Ian|title=Algeria 7–0 Tanzania|url=http://www.dzfoot.com/2015/11/17/algerie-tanzanie-live-tweet-77327.php|access-date=17 November 2015|publisher=DZfoot|date=16 January 2017}}</ref>

Mahrez was named in coach [[Georges Leekens]]' Algeria squad for the [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations]] in Gabon.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sofiane Feghouli left out of Algeria's final Africa Cup of Nations squad|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/38479829|access-date=15 January 2017|website=BBC Sport|date=31 December 2016}}</ref> In their opening game, he scored both goals in a 2–2 draw with [[Zimbabwe national football team|Zimbabwe]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Algeria 2 2 Zimbabwe|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/38545952|access-date=15 January 2017|website=BBC Sport|date=15 January 2017}}</ref> and was awarded Man of the Match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/CAF_Online/status/820694598624362496|title=R. Mahrez has been selected as the Total Man of the Match! Well done!|via=Twitter|publisher=CAF|date=15 January 2017}}</ref>

In October 2017, with Algeria's chances of reaching the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] already ended, Mahrez and his (at the time) Leicester teammate [[Islam Slimani]] were dropped from the national team, with coach [[Lucas Alcaraz]] selecting several new players.<ref>{{cite news|title=Algeria look to the future as Mahrez and Slimani are left out of World Cup qualifier|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41455809|access-date=6 October 2017|website=BBC Sport|date=1 October 2017}}</ref> On 18 November 2018, in the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations qualification|2019 Africa Cup of Nations qualifier]] Mahrez scored a brace in a 4–1 away victory against [[Togo national football team|Togo]], his first goal with the national team since [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations]] to lead Algeria to qualify for the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Afcon 2019: Mahrez brace helps Algeria qualify for Nations Cup|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46255664|access-date=18 November 2018|website=BBC Sport|date=18 November 2018}}</ref>

In May 2019, he was named to Algeria's 23-man squad for the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48464422|title=Africa Cup of Nations: Algeria announces 23-man squad|date=30 May 2019|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> By the decision of coach [[Djamel Belmadi]], Mahrez was chosen to be captain of Algeria at the Africa Cup of Nations.<ref>{{cite news|title=EN : le brassard de capitaine sera pour Riyad Mahrez ! |url=https://lagazettedufennec.com/equipe-nationale/selection-a/brassard-de-capitaine-sera-riyad-mahrez/ |access-date=8 July 2019|publisher=lagazettedufennec.com |date=11 June 2019}}</ref> Mahrez scored a 96-minute goal in a 2–1 win against [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] in the semi-finals of the competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/jul/14/algeria-nigeria-match-report|title=Riyad Mahrez strike sinks Nigeria and puts Algeria in Afcon final|website=The Guardian|date=14 July 2019}}</ref> Later on, Algeria managed to win the tournament which was their first since 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/live/football/49048899|title=Algeria celebrate second Afcon title after beating Senegal|website=BBC Sport|date=19 July 2019}}</ref>

Mahrez captained Algeria at the delayed [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations]], held in January 2022.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/africa/59780217|title=Mahrez set to lead Algeria at Afcon|work=BBC Sport }}</ref> In December 2023, he was named in the 26-man squad for the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.faf.dz/can-totalenergies-cote-divoire-2023-les-26-de-belmadi-pour-la-coupe-dafrique/|title=CAN TOTALENERGIES – COTE D'IVOIRE 2023 : LES 26 DE BELMADI POUR LA COUPE D'AFRIQUE|publisher=[[Algerian Football Federation]]|website=www.faf.dz|date=29 December 2023|access-date=30 December 2023|language=fr}}</ref>

On 21 March 2025, Mahrez featured in his 100th international match in a 3–1 away victory over [[Botswana national football team|Botswana]] during the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/articles/mahrez-algeria-100-caps |title=Mahrez makes it 100 not out |publisher=FIFA |date=21 March 2025 }}</ref> Later that year, on 9 October, he scored a goal in a 3–0 away victory against [[Somalia national football team|Somalia]], which ensured his nation's qualification for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Stevens |first=Rob |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c0knmp8x1rlt |title=Somalia 0–3 Algeria |publisher=BBC Sport |date=9 October 2025 }}</ref>

==Style of play==
A left-footed player, Mahrez usually plays as a [[right winger]], and has been regarded as one of the best wingers in world football.<ref>{{Cite web|title=The 10 Best Right-Wingers In The World Right Now, Named And Ranked|url=https://www.sportbible.com/football/53021-best-right-wingers-in-the-world-20210727|access-date=14 August 2021|website=www.sportbible.com|date=28 July 2021 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=The 5 Best Right Wingers in the World - Ranked|url=https://www.90min.com/posts/the-5-best-right-wingers-in-the-world-ranked|access-date=14 August 2021|website=90min.com|date=10 July 2020 |language=en-GB}}</ref> This position allows him to cut inside and shoot on goal with his stronger foot, or make [[Cross (association football)|deliveries]] into the penalty area; however, he is a versatile player, who is capable of playing anywhere across the front line, in a central role as an [[attacking midfielder]], as a winger on either flank, or even in a [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|centre-forward role]] as a [[Forward (association football)#False 9|false 9]]. A quick, creative and technically gifted player, his main traits are his trickery, balance, turn of pace, flair and [[Dribbling#Association football|dribbling]] skills. Although he is capable of scoring goals, he is also an excellent [[Assist (association football)|assist]] provider, courtesy of his ability to create chances for his teammates.<ref name="strada">{{cite news |url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Premier-League/22-03-2016/premier-mahrez-re-leicester-chi-talento-cresciuto-col-calcio-strada-1401130093840.shtml |title=Premier, Mahrez re di Leicester: chi è il talento cresciuto col calcio di strada? |work=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=it |last1=Boldrini |first1=Stefano |date=23 March 2016 |access-date=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ultimouomo.com/febbre-da-calciomercato-vol-1/ |title=Febbre da Calciomercato vol. 1 |publisher=www.ultimouomo.com |language=it |last1=Lisanti |first1=Francesco |date=16 July 2016 |access-date=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2699952-barcelona-transfer-news-latest-rumours-on-riyad-mahrez-and-jordi-alba |title=Barcelona Transfer News: Latest Rumours on Riyad Mahrez and Jordi Alba |publisher=Bleacher Report |last1=Jones |first1=Matt |date=25 March 2017 |access-date=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/analysis-mahrez-and-zahas-divergent-paths/1vegffv6b9lnn1g9fkkfbfr5z1 |title=Analysis: Mahrez and Zaha's divergent paths |publisher=Goal.com |last1=O'Conners |first1=James |date=23 January 2020 |access-date=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/club/manchester-city/382/blog/post/3684666 |title=Riyad Mahrez fits Pep Guardiola's template while adding something new to City |publisher=ESPN FC |last1=Cox |first1=Michael |date=30 October 2018 |access-date=18 July 2021 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2019/04/22/7-best-right-wingers-in-world-football/ |title=7 Best Right Wingers in World Football |publisher=www.hitc.com |last1=Potts Harmer |first1=Alfie |date=22 April 2019 |access-date=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2777465-leicester-city-reportedly-value-riyad-mahrez-at-75m-amid-man-city-rumours |title=Leicester City Reportedly Value Riyad Mahrez at £75M Amid Man City Rumours |publisher=Bleacher Report |last1=Jones |first1=Matt |date=23 May 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/us/features/manchester-city-how-the-false-nine-became-pep-guardiolas-plan-a |title=Manchester City: How the false nine became Pep Guardiola's Plan A |publisher=fourfourtwo.com |last1=Jolly |first1=Richard |date=5 March 2021 |access-date=29 April 2021 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/central-role-makes-mahrez-more-dangerous-says-leicester/2aljv3nj7xbj1tuf2fzj99uf4 |title=Central role makes Mahrez more dangerous, says Leicester City's Puel |publisher=www.goal.com |last1=Taiwo |first1=Taiye |date=30 October 2017 |access-date=29 April 2021 }}</ref> Despite his ability, however, his record from the [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] spot has been inconsistent throughout his career.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/10/08/penalty-taking-woes-riyad-mahrezs-conversion-rate-compares-others/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220111/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/10/08/penalty-taking-woes-riyad-mahrezs-conversion-rate-compares-others/ |archive-date=11 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |title=Penalty taking woes: How Riyad Mahrez's conversion rate compares to others in the Premier League |work=The Telegraph |last1=Field |first1=Pippa |date=5 October 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 }}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/man-city-penalty-mahrez-liverpool-15253082 |title=The Man City players with the best penalty records revealed after Riyad Mahrez miss vs Liverpool |work=The Manchester Evening News |last1=Brennan |first1=Stuart |date=8 October 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 }}</ref> In his youth, he was noted for his ball skills, but was often overlooked due to his slender build;<ref name=doyle/> when Quimper's youth manager Ronan Salaün and his assistant Mickaël Pellen first noticed Mahrez, they commented that he was talented, a good [[Free kick (association football)|set-piece]] taker, and he possessed excellent technique and dribbling skills with both feet, but that he was very slim and was lacking in the tactical aspect of the game, as he played primarily by instinct, having grown up playing [[Street football (association football)|street football]]; as such, after signing him, Salaün advised Mahrez to use his intelligence to avoid challenges, as he believed that he was not strong enough to withstand physical tackles.<ref name="street"/><ref name="strada"/>

Leicester's former head of recruitment, Steve Walsh noted upon observing Mahrez play that: "Riyad was a bit raw but he had a great touch. He could kill the ball dead and go past people. I liked his positivity. Some of his decision-making wasn't that great and defensively he wasn't the best, but you could see that he had real talent."<ref name="street"/> Mahrez has credited his former Leicester manager Claudio Ranieri for helping him to develop the tactical aspect of his game.<ref name="strada"/> During his time at Manchester City under manager Pep Guardiola, Mahrez was also able to improve his defensive skills and work-rate, as well as his decision-making.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/riyad-mahrez-man-city-pep-guardiola-changed-winger-tottenham-hotspur |title=How Pep Guardiola has transformed Riyad Mahrez from £60m substitute into the kind of winger he demands |publisher=FourFourTwo |last1=Wilkes |first1=Paul |date=16 August 2019 |access-date=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/mahrez-man-city-tactics-guardiola-17149849 |title=Man City star Riyad Mahrez pinpoints two parts of his game he has had to improve |work=The Manchester Evening News |last1=Brennan |first1=Stuart |date=25 October 2019 |access-date=5 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/mahrez-lifts-lid-on-his-initial-struggle-to-adapt-to/1tcofom30uusa1cd1wftpoglpl |title=Mahrez lifts lid on his initial struggle to adapt to Guardiola's demands at Manchester City |publisher=Goal.com |last1=Adewoye |first1=Gbenga |date=29 October 2019 |access-date=5 April 2020 }}</ref> Mahrez has developed his own special skill move dubbed as "La spéciale", in which he fakes a shot with his left foot, then he flicks the ball behind the right foot to dribble past his opponent.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/internacional/20201014/484078351334/mahrez-mexico.html |title="La especial": Mahrez bautiza así su regate ante México |website=Mundo Deportivo |language=es |date=14 October 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://videos.marca.com/v/0_4ckjjnq6-mahrez-presume-de-regate-de-fantasia-y-lo-bautiza-en-sus-redes-la-speciale?count=0 |title=Mahrez presume de regate de fantasía y lo bautiza en sus redes: "La spéciale" |website=Marca |date=14 October 2020 |language=es }}</ref>

Mahrez'z career is defined by his leadership, including captaining Algeria to their 2019 Africa Cup of Nations title with a decisive free-kick in the semi-final against Nigeria. His role in Algeria's push for the 2026 World Cup underscores his enduring influence, aiming to lead the team back to the global stage after their last appearance in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Riyad Mahrez at 100 caps: A century of brilliance for Algeria |url=https://www.cafonline.com/news/riyad-mahrez-at-100-caps-a-century-of-brilliance-for-algeria/ |access-date=23 March 2025 |website=Riyad Mahrez at 100 caps: A century of brilliance for Algeria |language=en-GB}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Mahrez married his British girlfriend, Rita Johal, in 2015.<ref name=doyle/><ref>{{cite web|title=Mais qui est Rita, la très jolie femme de Mahrez ?|url=http://www.sports.fr/football/angleterre/articles/rita-la-tres-jolie-femme-de-riyad-mahrez-1505289/|website=Sports.fr|access-date=6 June 2016|language=fr|date=30 April 2016}}</ref> Their daughter was born later that year.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Percy|first1=John|title='Flying' Riyad Mahrez coming to terms with dramatic ascent and comparisons with Lionel Messi|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/leicester-city/12048440/Flying-Riyad-Mahrez-coming-to-terms-with-dramatic-ascent-and-comparisons-with-Lionel-Messi.html |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220111/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/leicester-city/12048440/Flying-Riyad-Mahrez-coming-to-terms-with-dramatic-ascent-and-comparisons-with-Lionel-Messi.html |archive-date=11 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|access-date=27 April 2016|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=13 December 2015}}{{cbignore}}</ref> In June 2019, the couple, who by that time had two daughters, were ordered to pay a former nanny more than £3,600 in unpaid wages.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-manchester-48770058|title=Riyad Mahrez ordered to compensate nanny|date=26 June 2019|website=BBC News}}</ref> In October 2020, it was confirmed that Mahrez is now in a relationship with English model Taylor Ward after splitting from Johal.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fitzpatrick |first1=Katie |title=Dawn Ward's daughter Taylor goes Instagram official with Man City footballer Riyad Mahrez |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/showbiz-news/dawn-wards-daughter-taylor-goes-19175839 |access-date=28 October 2020 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=27 October 2020}}</ref> They announced their engagement on 21 June 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/showbiz-news/manchester-city-player-riyad-mahrez-20870869|title=Manchester City player Riyad Mahrez is engaged to Taylor Ward|first=Katie|last=Fitzpatrick|date=22 June 2021|website=Manchester Evening News}}</ref> The couple had a daughter in July 2022.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sansome |first=Jessica |date=9 July 2022 |title=Taylor Ward and Man City's Riyad Mahrez welcome first child and share cute name |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/showbiz-news/taylor-ward-announces-birth-daughter-24443204 |website=Manchester Evening News |language=en}}</ref>

Mahrez is a practising Muslim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/thriving-premier-league-shining-example-6842237|title=Thriving Premier League a shining example of multiculturalism in week of Paris terrorist attack|date=16 November 2015|access-date=28 April 2016|author=Dave Kidd|publisher=Daily Mirror}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Duchâteau|first1=Romain|title=Riyad Mahrez, l'enfant chéri de Sarcelles|url=http://www.sofoot.com/riyad-mahrez-l-enfant-cheri-de-sarcelles-207264.html|access-date=13 May 2016|publisher=SoFoot|date=29 August 2015|language=fr|archive-date=5 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505130958/http://www.sofoot.com/riyad-mahrez-l-enfant-cheri-de-sarcelles-207264.html|url-status=dead}}</ref> In June 2017, he made the [[Umrah]] pilgrimage to [[Mecca]].<ref>{{cite news|title=رياض محرز يؤدي مناسك العمرة في مكة المكرمة|url=https://arabic.cnn.com/sport/2017/06/12/mahrez-omrah-mecca-algeria|access-date=13 June 2017|publisher=CNN|date=12 June 2017|language=ar}}</ref>

In May 2020, Mahrez lost hundreds of thousands of pounds' worth of valuables after his penthouse apartment in Manchester was burgled.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pilling |first1=Kim |title=Riyad Mahrez: Luxury watches worth £300k stolen as Manchester City player's penthouse raided |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/riyad-mahrez-stolen-watches-raid-manchester-city-a9540951.html |access-date=31 May 2020 |work=The Independent |date=31 May 2020}}</ref>

